<HEADLINE> China Lost to Sweden in World Table Tennis Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 26 (Xinhua) -- China lost to Sweden 2-3
in the men's final of the 45th World Team Table Tennis
Championships at Putra Stadium here tonight.
</P>
<P>
Jorgen Persson, the 1991 world singles champion, clinched the
winning point when he fought back gallantly from a game down to
beat current world champion Liu Guoliang 18-21, 21-17, 21-18 when
the score level was tied up at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
Sweden stunned the 10,000-odd crowds when Jan-Ove Waldner
defeated Guoliang and Persson outclassed world number two Kong
Linghui in two games.
</P>
<P>
Waldner, 34, recovered from a slow start as he beat Guoliang 19-
21, 21-7, 23-21 in 32 minutes with Persson easily wrapped up his
encounter with Kong Linghui, who made numerous unforced errors 21-
17, 21-19 in 21 minutes.
</P>
<P>
However, China's third player Liu Guozheng played steadily to
reduce the gap to 1-2 when he outwitted Peter Karlsson 21-6, 21-16
in 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Kong Linghui then levelled the score as he overcame a tired
Waldner 21-9, 21-17 in 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The match of the day went to the fifth tie with Persson playing
Liu Guoliang who looked set to seal the 13th victory for China
when he forced Persson to make mistakes and took the opening game
21-18 in 12 minutes after leading 20-15.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Persson then led 15-10 in the second game but
Liu Guoliang levelled it to 15-all with his own services. Liu
Guoliang then sent the ball out three times and to the net two
times for Persson to wrap up the game 21-17 in 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
In the championship's decider, Persson and Liu Guoliang played
cautiously as they drew level at two-all, three-all and four-all
before the Chinese world number three raced to 12-9.
</P>
<P>
Both players looked tense but Persson's mental looked strong as
he played cautiously with a neck-to-neck score of 12-all, 13-all,
14-all, 15-all and 16-all before he collected two more points to
lead 18-17.
</P>
<P>
He allowed Liu Guoliang to grab another point in the closely
contest match before getting three points in a row with the
winning point coming after Liu Gualiang's return went out.
</P>
<P>
"I have been in the sport for many years as a coach and player.
This is the happiest moment in my career. The team is not only
good but they also have a strong fighting spirit," said Swedish
chief coach Ulf Carlsson.
</P>
<P>
"When we took a 2-0 lead, the pressure is on the Chinese team
because they are the world champions. But, when the score level,
the match is a lot of nerves but exciting. To win against China,
you must have a strong team in the deciding match. You see, when
there were down 2-0, they fought back and this show that how good
they are," added Carlsson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
