<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Solution to Cyprus Issue Desirable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 27 (Xinhua) --
Representatives from the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities on Cyprus met Sunday within the
framework of their efforts to promote
rapprochement and called for a settlement of the
Cyprus issue through a federal formula.
</P>
<P>
They met in the Pyla village in the Lanarca
district, south of the island, which is inhabited
by both Greek and Turkish Cypriots. Such a meeting
is rarely seen as Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash banned Turkish Cypriots from attending
most bicommunal meetings two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Members from both Cyprus' main opposition AKEL
party and Turkish Cypriot Patriotic Unity Movement
expressed the hope that the Cyprus issue would be
resolved through a federal formula, the Cyprus
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
AKEL parliamentary spokesman Andreas Christou
said the event aimed at accelerating
communications and rapprochement, removing
distrust, and cementing the efforts to bring the
two communities together so as to restore their
good ties and a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Izzet Izcan, general secretary of the Movement,
said that his Movement believes that maintaining
the unity of the country and its territorial
integrity is essential and a federal solution
which is based on political equality of the two
communities, a bizonal bicommunal solution is the
only way out at the moment.
</P>
<P>
He said "we will carry on with confidence
building measures to help our communities on both
sides to come together and to show the world that
people can come together, work together and live
together."
</P>
<P>
There are differences between the two
communities and "this is the only way to work them
out and bring peace to our country, which is all
of Cyprus," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready for a compromise," he said,
adding that "we cannot stick to the past."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot communities since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union
with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then the United Nations has been trying
to reunify the tiny island country through a
bizonal, bicommunal federation formula.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
