<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report on Deployment of Pro-Israel SLA in Cyprus Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Cypriots have
rejected an Israeli press report on deployment of the pro-Israeli
South Lebanese Army (SLA) militias in the Turkish Cypriots-
dominated north Cyprus, reported the Anatolia News Agency on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tahsin Ertugruloglu, a senior Turkish Cypriot official, said
over the weekend that the allegation was "ridiculous and baseless".
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into a Turkish Cypriots-controled part
and a Greek Cypriots-dominated part since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and occupied the northern third of the mediterranean island
in the wake of an aborted pro-Athens military coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The news was totally groundless, said Ertugruloglu. "Here is a
democratic and open land. Events take place in the eyes of
everybody."
</P>
<P>
The Tel Aviv-based Hebrew newspaper, Yediot Aharonot, published
a report claiming that the SLA militiamen and their families would
be deployed in the Turkish Cypriots-controled northern part of
Cyprus after Israeli troops withdraw from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Ever since he took office last year, Prime Minister Ehud Barak
has repeatedly declared to pull the Israeli forces out of Lebanon
in the year 2000, unilaterally if needed. Deployment of the SLA men
would be one of the issues that need to be solved under such a
scenario. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minor Quakes Jolt Turkey Over Weekend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- While aftershocks continue after
two strong earthquakes devastating west Turkey last year, minor
quakes shook other regions of the country over the weekend,
reported the Anatolia News Agency on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued by the Kandilli Observatory and
Seismology Center of Bogazici University in Istanbul, four quakes,
which were 4.4, 4.0, 3.8 and 4.2 degrees on Richter scale
respectively, occurred in the Turkey-Iraq border region Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, four tremors measuring 4.0, 3.2, 3.1 and 3.1 degrees
respectively on Richter scale shook other places across the
country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, four aftershocks were registered in west Turkey in
the two consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is an earthquake-prone country known to be standing on
the Eurasia faults. In 1999, the country was visited by a 7.4-
magnitude earthquake on August 17 and then a 7.2-magnitude tremor
on November 12, both in west Turkey. Altogether 18,000 people were
killed and more than 43,000 injured. The property losses were
estimated at 20 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
