<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Starts Coal Development Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has begun a
feasibility study on coal development in Oromiya State, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Studies have shown the availability of 500 million tons of coal
deposit in Illubabor Zone of Oromiya State.
</P>
<P>
The coal if developed could be used as raw material for the
production of fertilizers and as replacement of fuel oil, the
report quoted the project manager Lelisa Daba as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia imports 87,000 tons of urea and other fertilizers
annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 33 Bus Passengers Die in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-three Zimbabweans died
and an unknown number missing after a bus was swept downstream
Friday when the driver tried to cross the flooded Mudzi river,
police spokesman Wayne Bvudzijena said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told the Zimbabwe News Agency that the bus was
going to Rwenya, about 15 kilometers from Nyamapanda on the
northeastern border.
</P>
<P>
"When they approached the Mudzi River Bridge, the river was in
floods and the driver decided to stop briefly until the water
subsided," he said.
</P>
<P>
"However when a bus from another company crossed safely, the
passengers in the bus and those who had disembarked from the first
bus urged the driver to drive across. Unfortunately the
Chawasarira bus was swept away," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said so far 33 bodies had been recovered and 27 of these had
been identified.
</P>
<P>
There were 18 survivors from the accident, including the
driver. The conductor did not survive, making it impossible to
determine the number of passengers who had been in the bus.
</P>
<P>
Bvudzijena said passengers from the first bus who had
disembarked out of fear of their bus being swept away, had also
jumped into the Chawasarira bus as it made its fateful attempt.
</P>
<P>
Bus drivers have on numerous occasions been warned not to
attempt to cross flooded rivers, but these warnings have fallen on
deaf ears which has resulted in the loss of hundreds of lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
