<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The Dubai government has set an ambitious target to
turn the emirate into an international center for business and
investments by drawing up a 2000-2010 development plan.
</P>
<P>
The plan focused on diversifying the emirate's economic basis,
improving production capacity by providing skilled work force and
creating favorable climate for investments, said a report by the
Dubai Chamber of Commerce and Industry,
</P>
<P>
Dubai's population will rise to 1.2 million in the year 2005
against an estimated 906,000 this year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that the processing industries sector will
need an investment of 3.2 million U.S. dollars in the coming years,
the water and electricity sector 1.6 million dollars, the
communications sector 4.6 million dollars, 1.4 million dollars for
the trade sector and 1.1 million dollars for other sectors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Dubai government is expecting an annual growth
rate
in the gross domestic product (GDP) of some 5 percent, a growth
rate of 6.9 percent in non-oil sectors and an increase of
contribution of
the non-oil sectors to the GDP to 88.74 percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian government has finalized the public
budget for the fiscal year 2000-2001 which was projected at 110
billion Egyptian pounds (31.88 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, top priority was given to those projects for
social development and the biggest part of resources will come from
revenues of the oil sector, the Suez Canal and expanded tax
collection.
</P>
<P>
However, the budget did not levy new taxes on people with low or
medium income.
</P>
<P>
It set aside 13 million pounds (3.77 million dollars) for
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
It also predicted that total investments will rise to
more than 70 billion pounds (20.29 billion dollars) to implement
such mega projects as Tushka, developing the Upper Egypt and the
national
technological schemes in addition to projects in the fields of
education, health and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab countries saw their exports volume stand at 134
billion U.S. dollars in 1999, accounting for 2.4 percent of that of
the world, while imports volume at about 147.5 billion dollars, or
2.6 percent of the world imports volume.
</P>
<P>
A report, jointly prepared by the Arab League, Arab Monetary
Fund, the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OAPEC )
and Arab Fund for Economic Development(AFED), said that the
total value of inter-exports reached 14.6 billion dollars. And Arab

countries spent 151.4 billion dollars on servicing public debts.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) of Arab countries amounted to
590 billion dollars and the average economic growth rate fell from
3.6 percent in 1998 to 2.5 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria produced 3,000 tons of dates in 1999. Date,
which has 22 types in the country, is grown on an area of 700
hectares in the central province of Tadmor and 293 hectares in Bu-
Kamal.
</P>
<P>
Syria has 176,000 date palms 70,000 out of which are yielding
ones at present.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian Agriculture Ministry attaches great importance to
growing dates and it has set up four centers for breeding date
palms which serve as genetic mothers for different locally-produced
and imported breeds. The centers sort out the high quality types
that best suit the Syrian climate, said sources of the Farming
Affairs
Department of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The General Organization for Seed Breeding built a laboratory
for breeding date palms and has imported 10,000 saplings of the
best types, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
