<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Highlights Egypt's Role in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Israeli Justice Minister
Yossi Beilin said here Sunday that Egypt is a pillar of the Middle
East peace process whose national interest requires peace making in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak was working for peace and his
frequent meetings with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat were part
of his efforts in the pursuit of peace, Beilin told reporters after
meeting with Mubarak in the day.
</P>
<P>
President Mubarak would meet with other leaders in the region
soon in a bid to move forward the stalled peace process and make
parties concerned understand each other in a better way, he added.
</P>
<P>
President Mubarak was optimistic at the possibility of
overcoming the current difficulties within the coming months, said
the minister. The leaders in the region are generally willing to
see peace prevailing in the Middle East and are well aware of the
price involved, he said, indicating that the Arabs are ready to pay
the price, but not any price.
</P>
<P>
Although the Arabs are feeling down about the deadlocked peace
talks, said Beilin, they understand that the chances for making
peace are still there and they are willing to grasp the chances.
</P>
<P>
There is no more time to waste and the atmosphere has to change
as soon as possible to break the impasse in the peace talks on the
Palestinian, Syrian and Lebanese tracks.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the provocative statements recently made by
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy on Lebanon, Beilin said what is
important is peace and not talk.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said he has known Levy for years as a man committed to
peace even after he became a member of the hardline Likud party
because he voted for peace many times, adding that as a foreign
minister he should adhere to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that Levy's remarks that Israeli soldiers
would leave Lebanon in less than 130 days, were not acceptable and
did not come at the right time.
</P>
<P>
Levy, addressing the Knesset (parliament)last week, threatened
to make Beirut pay "blood for blood, soul for soul, child for
child" if Israel was attacked from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Beilin added that Israel was not concerned with labelling the
Lebanese Hezbollah as a group of freedom fighters or terrorists and
that his country was giving top priority now to closing this file.
</P>
<P>
On Israel's repeated talks about the importance of peacemaking
without taking genuine steps, Beilin said that a line should be
drawn between the situation in the Palestinian self-rule areas and
that in Lebanon because bombing Lebanon is not a goal in itself and
Israel is ready to get out of Lebanon as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he reiterated what Israel had been claiming that it
was ready to pull out of the agreed-upon 6.1 percent from the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is committed to working for peace, he
said, and it wants to resolve the Israeli-Palestinian issue this
year.
</P>
<P>
The two parties know each other well and are willing to foot the
bill even if one or the other party was a bit intransigent on a
given point, he added.
</P>
<P>
On peace with Syria, he said Israel is ready to pay the price
for peace with Syria and is also ready to pull out of Lebanon and
reach a settlement with the Palestinians. But this did not mean
that it would meet all the Palestinian demands.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are negotiating out of mutual appreciation and the
desire to reach a final solution quickly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has a role to play in the peace talks and the confidence-
building, Beilin said, adding that President Mubarak also has a
role in boosting peace prospects and bridging the gap in viewpoints
of the parties concerned, he said, voicing hope that hurdles could
be overcome.
</P>
<P>
The returns of peacemaking in 2000 will be high in the region,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis want to reach a compromise with the Palestinians
and there is no adamant position on the 6.1 percent land transfer
and the two sides could reach an agreement though the 1993 Oslo
accord did not require such an agreement on handing over lands, he
claimed.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said that a final solution is more important than the 6.1
percent which was only part of the interim phase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
