<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Admits No Certainty of Agreement on Lebanon Pullout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak admitted Sunday that there is no certainty that Israel will
reach a deal with Syria and Lebanon before the promised deadline
for Israeli troops withdrawal from south Lebanon in July.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks at a special cabinet session on Israel's
Lebanon policy, which was the first thorough cabinet debate on the
issue since the current government came to power nearly eight
months ago.
</P>
<P>
The ministers focused their debate on Barak's proposal to bring
Israeli soldiers based in the Israeli-occupied buffer zone in south
Lebanon back home by July 7 "with or without an agreement" with
Lebanon and Syria, the main foreign power broker in Lebanon,
according to Israel Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
Barak reaffirmed that the pullout from Lebanon will serve
Israel's national interests in the long run and therefore, Israel
should go back to its international border with Lebanon and defend
its northern territory from there.
</P>
<P>
Despite the uncertainty of an agreement, Barak also expressed
the hope that the withdrawal could be carried out under a peace
deal in hand, saying that the door to the negotiations with Syria
and Lebanon is still open.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet debate, held at the request of Transport Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, was still going on after several hours of
discussions in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The lengthy meeting, which was scheduled to last more than eight
hours, will give every minister a chance to express his or her
opinion toward the pullout plan.
</P>
<P>
Israel unilaterally set up a buffer zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with a self-declared purpose of protecting its northern border
areas from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli army has encountered fierce resistence in the
zone from Lebanese Shiite Muslim militant group Hezbollah since
then, which has claimed at least 200 lives of Israel soldiers.
</P>
<P>
To turn the trend, Barak promised to bring his soldiers back
home by July 7 this year, a year after he was elected prime
minister. He expected that the withdrawal will strip Syria's last
card on the negotiation table, and then lead to a permanent peace
agreement with Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Israel resumed their peace talks last December after a
45-month deadlock, however, the talks hit a snag again earlier this
year only after two rounds due to differences over Israel's
withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which it seized from Syria in
the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
The recent flare-up of fighting between Israeli troops and
Hezbollah guerrillas in south Lebanon and the Israeli bombing of
Lebanese civilain targets in the past few weeks have dashed hopes
that Israel and Lebanon can reach a peace agreement in July.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock in the Syrian and Lebanese peace tracks had made
some military experts worry that a unilateral withdrawal of Israeli
army will be a catastrophic retreat in disorder, accompanied by "
convulsions" and clashes in the course of redeployment.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Barak will ask Sunday's cabinet meeting to
declare that the government is determined to withdraw the Israel
Defense Forces from Lebanon with an agreement, but will reassess
the situation in two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
