<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak: U.S. Wants Israeli-Syrian Deal by May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Sunday that U.S. President Bill Clinton wants Israel and
Syria to reach a peace agreement by May, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks at a weekly cabinet meeting, the first
thorough cabinet debate of its kind on Israel's Lebanon policy
after the current government came to power nearly eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
Linking the Israeli troops pullout from Lebanon with peace
contacts with Syria, the major power broker in Lebanon, Barak said
the political clock of President Clinton was ticking and the
American leader wanted an Israeli-Syrian peace deal by May.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, the ardent sponsor of the Middle East peace process,
will hesitate to make any major political efforts to revive the
process in the second half of this year, when the U.S. 2000
presidential campaign gets into a white heat, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
However, the president is reportedly eager to ensure
comprehensive peace in the region before then in order to turn his
farewell party into a victory celebration and lay the carpet to the
award ceremony of a Nobel Peace Prize at his feet.
</P>
<P>
Barak made another surprise announcement during Sunday's cabinet
discussions that Yitzhak Rabin, when he was prime minister,
signaled to Americans that Israel would withdraw from the Golan
Heights to the June 4, 1967 lines under certain conditions. Israel
used to deny that Rabin had ever made such an oral promise.
</P>
<P>
Barak also told his ministers that the secret contacts with
Syria conducted by former prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
government through U.S. businessman Ron Lauder, were also under the
assumption of the withdrawal position.
</P>
<P>
Barak stressed that the door to the negotiation with Syria and
Lebanon is still open. He hinted Israel regards Syria's promises on
security arrangements, normalization, demilitarization and the
solution to water issue as "certain conditions".
</P>
<P>
These remarks made some analysts speculate that Barak will
concede to Syria's demand for a written promise about Golan Heights
withdrawal before their negotiations could resume.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks, resumed last December after a
45-month break, hit a snag again earlier this year only after two
rounds of talks due to differences over Israeli troops withdrawal
form the Golan Heights, which was occupied by Israel in the 1967
Middle East war. 
</P>
<P>
Syria is demanding Israel's public pledge to a full withdrawal
to the June 4, 1967 borders. But Israel insisted on discussion of
security arrangements and normalization of bilateral ties first.
</P>
<P>
The focus of Sunday's cabinet meeting was Barak's proposal to
bring Israeli soldiers in the Israeli-occupied buffer zone in South
Lebanon back home by July 7 "with or without an agreement" with
Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The lengthy meeting, held at the request of Transport Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, gave every minister a chance to express his or
her opinion toward the pullout plan.
</P>
<P>
Barak reaffirmed during his two-hour briefing that the pullout
from Lebanon will ensure Israel's national interests in the long
run and therefore, Israel should go back to its international
border with Lebanon and defend its northern territory from there.
</P>
<P>
But some ministers expressed their worries about a unilateral
withdrawal without an agreement, which according to some military
experts will be a catastrophic retreat in disorder, accompanied
by "convulsions" and clashes in the course of redeployment.
</P>
<P>
After more than six hours, the meeting ended with no decisions
announced. It is reported that the deliberations would continue
next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Israel unilaterally set up a buffer zone in South Lebanon in
1985 with a self-declared purpose of protecting its northern border
areas from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli army had encountered fierce fightback in the
zone from Lebanese Shiite Muslim militant group Hezbollah since
then, which left at least 200 deaths of Israel soldiers.
</P>
<P>
To turn the trend, Barak promised to bring his soldier back home
by July 7, a year after he was elected prime minister. He expected
the pullout will cancel Syria's last card on the negotiation table,
and then lead to a permanent peace agreement with Syria and
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, the recent flare-up of fighting between Israeli
soldiers and Hezbollah guerrillas in South Lebanon and Israel's
bombing of Lebanese civilian targets in the past few weeks have
dashed hopes that Israel and Lebanon can reach a peace agreement
before July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
