<HEADLINE> Nigeria Stresses Traditional Rulers' Role in Social Harmony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Vice President Atiku
Abubakar has called on the nation's traditional rulers to ensure
the peaceful co- existence among the diverse ethnic groups in
their domains, the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Calling them custodians of the country's unique culture, he
said in Lafia traditional ruler's domain in central Nigeria's
Nassarawa State that " what has happened in Kaduna State is
something to be condemned by all decent human beings".
</P>
<P>
About 300 people died in last week's clash between Christians
and Moslems in the country's northern city Kaduna.
</P>
<P>
The NAN quoted Abubakar as saying in a turbaning ceremony
performed by the Emir of Lafia, Assarawa State, at which the
Nassarawa State's Governor Alhaji Adamu presented the traditional
ruler with the staff of office.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that irrespective of their ethnic differences and
religious background, Nigerians should live with each other in
peace and harmony.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Senate President Chuba Okadigbo and Speaker of the
House of Representatives Alhaji Na'abba were among the guests to
attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
