<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Export Up in First Two Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's export turnover in the
first two months of this year reached 1.95 billion U.S. dollars,
an increase of 34.8 percent over the same period last year,
Vietnam News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
To this figure, foreign-invested businesses contributed 505
million U.S. dollars or a year-on-year increase of 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam's biggest economic hub, earned 907
million U.S. dollars, up by 47.4 percent as compared to the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding exported goods of the country include coal, 519
million U.S. dollars, and sea products, 131 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Vietnam has so far this year exported 147,000 tons of
rice, lower than planned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's import turnover totalled 2 billion U.S.
dollars, up by 28.9 percent as compared to the corresponding
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign-invested businesses made an import turnover worth
583 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam planned to reach the export turnover target of 12
billion U.S. dollars this year or an increase of 12 percent over
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Corporation Takes Over British Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DElHI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- In the biggest-ever deal in
Indian corporate history, Tata Tea Limited (TTL) has bought out
all the brands of British Tetley Tea for 271 million pounds
sterlings (some 434 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The acquisition of the worldwide Tetley tea business, which is
twice the size of Tata Tea, a branch company of the Tata Group,
represents the largest cross-border takeover of an international
brand by an Indian company.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed on Saturday night in Mumbai, 1,
400 kilometers southwest of New Delhi, TTL would, through a 100
percent subsidiary in Britain, make a formal offer for acquiring
all the shareholding of the Tetley group, the Press Trust of India
(PTI) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The takeover includes the private label tea business in the
United States but excludes its coffee business there, which was
recently sold by the existing shareholders separately.
</P>
<P>
Tata Group Chairman Ratan Tata reportedly said at the signing
ceremony that it was a momentous occasion for the Tatas as this
was the largest ever acquisition by an Indian company abroad in
terms of acquiring an international brand.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition of Tetley, which has an annual sales of some
439 million dollars, will be financed with 70 million pound
sterlings of equity, of which 60 million pound sterlings would
come from TTL and 10 million pound sterlings will be from Tata Tea
Inc., a Tata subsidiary based in New York.
</P>
<P>
TTL vice chairman R K Krishna Kumar said the debt component of
20 million pound sterlings would be raised through instruments
like subordinate vendor loan notes and debt offerings arranged by
Rabo Bank, which acted as the financial and strategic advisor as
well as sole lead manager for this transaction.
</P>
<P>
Kumar estimated that the combined turnover of Tetley and Tata
would be at 28 to 29 billion rupees (some 651 to 674 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Tetley had a market share of 22 percent in the United Kingdom
while it was the number two in the U.S. market with a share of 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
The deal took a long time as the huge process of due diligence
had to be completed, he said, adding the venture capitalists had
sold the coffee business only on February three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
