<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, February 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. authorities Saturday expelled a Cuban
diplomat ignoring an expulsion order and put him on a flight bound
for Montreal, Canada, where he will be flown to Cuba's capital of
Havana.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat, Jose Imperatori, earlier Saturday announced he
went on a hunger strike to protest the U.S. expulsion order.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department announced last week Imperatori should
leave the United States by 1:30 p.m. Saturday and his diplomatic
privileges and immunities will be removed after the deadline. (U.
S.-Cuba-Diplomat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Chinese ambassador to the United States, Li
Zhaoxing, Saturday urged all peace-loving Americans to take
actions to defeat the Taiwan Security Enhancement Act (TSEA) and
help secure congressional approval of permanent Normal Trade
Relations (NTR) for China.
</P>
<P>
He also asked Americans to oppose U.S. arms sales to Taiwan and
other actions that go against the spirit of the three joint
communiques between Beijing and Washington so as to ensure a sound
and stable relationship between the two countries. (China-U.S.-
Relations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Apparently trying to ward off the controversy caused
by Prime Minister Lionel Jospin's remarks in the Middle East,
French President Jacques Chirac has stressed that his country's
Middle East policy remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the clarification in a telephone conversation with
Jospin on Saturday night after Jospin said in Jerusalem on
Thursday that the attacks by Hezbollah guerrillas on Israeli
occupation troops in southern Lebanon were "terrorist acts".
</P>
<P>
He said that France's attitude toward Israel and Arab countries
should be one of "impartiality", said a communique released by the
Elysee presidential palace on Sunday morning. (France-Mideast-
Policy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Almost all the 79 remaining passengers of the
hijacked Afghan plane, which landed at a London airport earlier
this month, are to be deported after their applications for asylum
were found to be bogus.
</P>
<P>
The British government will make such an announcement within
the next two days, The Sunday Telegraph newspaper said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
That decision is expected to meet protests from refugee
organizations and is certain to face legal challenges which will
prolong the passengers' stay in Britain for at least another month,
the report said. (Britain-Afghanistan-Hijacked Plane)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Columns of ash started to spew from Iceland's most
active volcano Hekla at about 1715 GMT Saturday in its first
eruption for almost 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, lava began to flow from Hekla at a speed of 10 to
15 kilometers an hour, which is 150 kilometers southeast of the
capital Reykjavik. According to an Icelandic radio station, up to
early Sunday morning, the lava had already flowed over 10
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
As there are few people living around the volcano, the eruption
would pose no danger to life and property, but the smoke and ash
from the eruption have caused difficulty for people living in
farther areas. (Iceland-Vocano-Eruption) 
</P>
</TEXT>
