<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resistance Against Occupation is People's Legitimate Right: Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said it is the legitimate right of the people to resist occupiers,
the official Middle East News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Germany's Der Spiegel magazine to be
published Monday, Mubarak noted that Lebanese Hezbollah group is
fighting Israeli occupation and that the Israeli soldiers killed
in the Israeli-occupied zone were in Lebanese territories.
</P>
<P>
Seven Israeli soldiers have been killed by Lebanese guerrillas
in South Lebanon since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak criticized Israel for "making a fuss" over his recent
visit to Lebanon and accused the Jewish state of trying to turn the
United States against Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak visited Lebanon on February 19, the first-ever visit by
an Egyptian president, after Egypt expressed concern about the
stalemate in the Middle East peace process and support for Lebanon
following the large-scale Israeli air raids against Lebanese
civilian targets on February 8.
</P>
<P>
His visit to Lebanon was aimed only to show support to the
Lebanese "who are feeling that they are alone in the ring," Mubarak
said.
</P>
<P>
The president warned that Israel's continued bombing of Lebanon,
which has injured dozens of civilians and devastated three power
plants in Lebanon, has further diminished its credibility.
</P>
<P>
However, Mubarak ruled out the possibility of another war in the
Middle East region, while he cautioned that if peace was not
achieved, the region would be more vulnerable to violence.
</P>
<P>
He called on Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak to "stop his
circumventions and manoeuvres" and take brave decisions to withdraw
from the Golan Heights it seized from Syria in 1967, saying that "
peace will benefit it more than war."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak noted that the Middle East peace process would not be
settled unless the Palestinian issue, the center piece of Arab-
Israeli conflict, is resolved.
</P>
<P>
Although Egypt and Israel signed a peace treaty in 1979, they
have been keeping what many analysts called "cold peace." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Asks U.S. to Stop Meddling in Others'  Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR , February 27 (Xinhua) Malaysia asks the
United States to stop behaving like the world's policeman and to
stay out of other countries' internal affairs, according to the
local daily "The Sun" Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"They should stay out of other countries' internal affairs and
stop passing judgment on others," Minister in the Prime Minister's
Department Rais Yatim was quoted as saying in response to the US
State Department's annual report on global human rights abuse,
which reportedly criticized Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The minister said "They should instead look at their own
backyard first as the number of human rights violations in the US
itself is horrendous.
</P>
<P>
"The rampant human rights violations taking place in the Bronx
area in New York, for example, were never told to the world...so
before meddling in other people's affairs, they should look into
theirs first," the minister told the daily.
</P>
<P>
Rais said every country has its own set of sovereign laws and
therefore, the US should not pass judgment.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that there is not one system in the world which
is above criticism, the minister said Malaysia has prospered under
its own democratic governance.
</P>
<P>
He said "I urge the State Department to stay out of our
internal affairs because we are surely not going to submit to its
judgment."
</P>
<P>
The State Department's report reportedly stated that Anwar
Ibrahim's case was "indicative of human rights violations in that
country". Anwar who was former Deputy Prime Minister and sacked in
September 1998 were sentenced to six-years' imprisonment for
corrupt practices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
