<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Grant Aid to Control Iodine Deficiency in  Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The grant assistance will be used for supplying 130 metric tons
of potassium iodate, and training, monitoring and evaluation of
the project in collaboration with Bangladesh Small and Cottage
Industries Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is one of the countries most affected by iodine
deficiency disorders in the world. To overcome this problem,
Bangladesh started implementing CIDD in 1990 with the assistance
of UNICEF by universal iodization of salt in all salt factories
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Control of iodine deficiency and disorders has proved to be the
most cost-effective and successful public health program in
Bangladesh.Preliminary data from national survey indicated a
steady reduction in number of population at risk, with low iodine
level down from 69 percent in 1993 to 40 percent in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
