<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Sci-fi Copyright Infringement Case Reported in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- China may permanently stop the
presses at a literary magazine that has pirated the copyright of a
science fiction periodical.
</P>
<P>
This is the first case of copyright infringement of science
fiction in China, where the genre has long been controversial.
</P>
<P>
Liu Bo, an official with the State Press and Publications
Administration, told Xinhua that Hebei-based Popular Literature
magazine will be possibly closed down, because it published
stories and photos carried by Science Fiction World, the country's
most renowned sci-fi periodical and a winner of the World's Best
Sci-Fi Magazine award issued by the World Sci-Fi Organization.
</P>
<P>
Internet chat rooms are buzzing with discussions about the
unusual case, as science fiction was taboo here until just a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, it was regarded as "spiritual pollution" and "
pseudoscience" and was banned from publishing, while science
fiction writers were looked down upon by others.
</P>
<P>
Official newspapers criticized some sci-fi stories, saying
their detailed predictions of gloom for the future "could possibly
lead to chaos and social instability."
</P>
<P>
Sci-fi did not stage a comeback until the mid-1990s, when
Chinese authorities stressed that science and man's imagination
are vital for the nation's creativity and competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's national university entrance exam used
science fiction as the theme in the essay writing portion of the
test, causing a tremendous reaction in society, saying that this
is helpful to fostering students' imagination.
</P>
<P>
"Piracy is to be condemned, but this case does show that
science fiction is for the first time widely accepted in China
which had for 5,000 years seen imagination and free thinking as a
threat," said sci-fi writer Zheng Jun.
</P>
<P>
He said the case demonstrates that China is changing from a
traditional society into a modern one and that people are paying
more attention to the future than the past.
</P>
<P>
Sci-fi, a genre of literature mainly exploring change and the
future, is considered to be a product of the industrial revolution
in Western countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Investigated Wrongdoing of 700 Prosecutors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- China's procuratorial bodies
in charge of anti-corruption and supervision over law enforcement
have stepped up efforts in wiping out corruption from within their
own ranks.
</P>
<P>
Last year 694 prosecutors involved in 606 cases were
investigated for wrongdoing by disciplinary and supervision
departments of people's procuratorates across the country, the
Supreme People's Procuratorate (SPP) said today.
</P>
<P>
A national conference on disciplinary and supervision work held
by the SPP was told that investigations have been concluded for 88.
6 percent of the cases, in which 544 prosecutors were given
disciplinary punishment, 55 went to trial and 73 were criticized
and required to be educated.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ke, head of the working group of the Central Commission
for Disciplinary Inspection of the Chinese Communist Party
stationed in the SPP, delivered a work report at today's
conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that "procuratorates cross the country have seen a
pleasing turn for the better in aspects of honesty, self-
discipline, and fair and rigorous enforcement of the law thanks to
the power of political and ideological education."
</P>
<P>
Following a new rule that the head of a procuratorate will be
held responsible for corruption cases uncovered in his work unit,
top prosecutors in eight provinces were ordered to Beijing to
criticize their own mistakes in 1999, and 33 other regional
prosecutors reviewed their responsibilities to offices at higher
levels.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-nine heads of procuratorates across the country were
investigated and affixed for their responsibilities in 79 cases,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He told disciplinary bodies of procuratorates to intensify
their supervision over officials, especially heads of
procuratorates, law enforcement procedures, appointments and
replacements, financial accounts of prosecution offices and off-
duty activities of prosecutors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
