<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Japan, ROK Agree on More Cooperation in Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The environment ministers of
China, Japan and the Republic of Korea (ROK) issued a joint
communique here today, outlining their future priority areas of
regional cooperation in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The communique, signed today by the ministers at the end of a
two-day meeting, said the three countries will strengthen their
cooperation in environmental protection projects at both regional
and international levels.
</P>
<P>
The ministers have already considered proposals for
cooperation in publicity campaigns to raise public awareness about
environmental problems, for projects involving prevention of fresh
water pollution and land-based marine pollution, and cooperation
among the environmental industry.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of the State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA) of China, Kayoko Shimizu, director-general
of Japan's Environment Agency, and Kim Myung-Ja, ROK environment
minister, commended the efforts of the three countries in
promoting the ongoing joint projects, the document said.
</P>
<P>
Included are the Acid Deposition Monitoring Network in East
Asia, and the three countries' joint research project on Long-
range Transportation of Air Pollutants.
</P>
<P>
The document also calls for cooperation between the three
countries in habitat conservation and restoration of damaged
ecosystems so as to protect bio-diversity and better manage
sustainable water resources.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the second after the first one held in Seoul last
year, aimed at carrying out the environmental protection
agreements reached during separate summit meetings between the
three countries in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
