<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Leader Demands Apology from French PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A leader of the Lebanese
Hezbollah on Sunday demanded that French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin apologize for branding guerrilla attacks against Israeli
occupation troops as "terrorist" acts.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah Deputy Secretary General Sheikh Naem Kassem said
Jospin should make an apology if he wants to visit Lebanon in the
future since he has become persona non grata for his "obvious
insult against the resistance movement and the Lebanese people."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he acclaimed the demonstration staged by Palestinian
students during Jospin's visit to the Birzeit University in the
West Bank city of Ramallah on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 students, angered by Jospin's remarks about Hezbollah
resistance, confronted the French premier and hurled stones at him
when he was leaving the campus after addressing the university
teachers and student representative.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat condemned the attack and
ordered the university to be closed for three days.
</P>
<P>
Kassam said the Palestinian students regarded Jospin's remarks
as hostile and inconsistent with the French claimed policy of
supporting Lebanese sovereignty and the French role in the
committee overseeing conflicts between Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The committee, grouping representatives from the United States,
France, Syria, Lebanon and Israel, was formed in August 1996 under
the understanding reached between Hezbollah and Israel after a
massive Israeli attacks on Lebanon, killing 200 civilians.
</P>
<P>
Jospin, on the second day of his four-day visit in Jerusalem,
said Thursday "France condemns Hezbollah's attacks, and all types
of terrorist attacks which may be carried out against soldiers or
possibly Israel's civilian population."
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the remarks, Hezbollah issued a statement Friday
accusing that Jospin's stance was hostile, racist and went against
the French principles and French interests in the Middle East
region.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian- and Syrian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, is
spearheading Lebanese resistance against Israeli occupation of
southern Lebanese border areas where Israel carved out a buffer
zone with the claimed aim of protecting its north from cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
