<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Christians in Nigeria's northern
state of Kuduna, where religious conflicts took a death toll of
some 300 last week, Saturday called upon the federal government to
spilt the state into two.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, Sunday quoted
Archbishop Peter Jatau, Chairman of the 19 Northern States
Christian Association of Nigeria (CAN), as saying that "my candid
appeal to President Olusegun Obasanjo is to create a new Kaduna."
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there is any other way for the solution of
Kaduna problem, " the religious leader said.
</P>
<P>
Jatau told a federal government delegation responsible for
investigating last week's havoc that Kaduna state, where
Christians and Moslems are almost evenly divided, has seen too
many unfortunate accidents.
</P>
<P>
He cited the examples of the Kafanchan riot in 1987, Zango
Kataf crisis in 1992, Jema'a emir installation in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The federal delegation, consisting of Nigeria's Minister of
Internal Affairs Sunday Afolabi, Minister of State for Education
Alhaji Batagarawa, Minister of Women Affairs Ayeshatu Ismail and
Minister of Solid Mineral Development Alhaji Gwadabe, is currently
in an opinion listening process in Kaduna state before giving
suggestions to President Obasanjo. 
