<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcano Hekla Erupts in Iceland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Columns of ash started to
spew from Iceland's most active volcano Hekla at about 1715 GMT
Saturday in its first eruption for almost 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, lava began to flow from Hekla at a speed of 10 to
15 kilometers an hour , which is 150 kilometers southeast of the
capital Reykjavik. According to an Icelandic radio station, up to
early Sunday morning, the lava had already flowed over 10
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
As there are few people living around the volcano, the eruption
would pose no danger to life and property, but the smoke and ash
from the eruption have caused difficulty for people living in
farther areas.
</P>
<P>
Disregarding government warning about not to going too close to
Hekla, many local residents, especially residents from Reykjavik,
drove on Saturday night to enjoy the rare wintry landscape of fire
against the snowy background.
</P>
<P>
Hekla has erupted over 20 times since the 11th century, and its
last eruption was in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
