<HEADLINE> China's Everbright Bank Investing in Security Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Everbright Bank of China
underwrote 18.6 percent of the shares in Shenyin and Wanguo
Securities Co. to become its biggest shareholder, EBC's chairman
of the board Liu Mingkang announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The move of buying 246 million shares from the Industry and
Commerce Bank of China in China's oldest securities company is
part of EBC's preparation for a new round of stiff competition
with international counterparts, said Liu, the new chairman of the
board of Shenyin and Wanguo.
</P>
<P>
With registered capital worth 1.3 billion yuan, Shenyin and
Wanguo is now the largest stock trading company in the Shanghai
Stock Exchange and the fourth biggest in the Shenzhen Stock
Exchange. It concluded transactions worth 625 billion yuan (75
billion U.S. dollars) and earned 800 million yuan (96 million U.S.
dollars) in profits last year.
</P>
<P>
Directly affiliated to the State Council, EBC is China's first
foreign share-holding commercial bank. It now operates banking,
securities, issuance and asset management businesses. Its share
holders include China Everbright Bank, the Everbright Securities
Co. Ltd., and Sino-overseas equity insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
It has six subsidiaries listed in Hong Kong and Singapore.
</P>
