<HEADLINE> Iraq, Turkey Open Talks on Trade, Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir
Muhammad Rashid and visiting Turkish State Minister Edip Safter
Gaydali held talks here Sunday on trade and economic ties, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Rashid stressed that the visit of the 200-
member Turkish delegation headed by Gaydali, which arrived here on
Saturday, reflects the depth of bilateral trade and economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
"We will exert much efforts to establish distinguished relations
between the two countries," said Rashid.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Gaydali affirmed Turkey's readiness to ensure
needs of the Iraqi market within the framework of the United
Nations oil-for-food program, which allows Iraq to sell limited
amount of oil to buy humanitarian goods under U.N. supervision for
its people.
</P>
<P>
He extended gratitude for the assistance Iraq offered to the
victims of two major earthquakes striking Turkey last year.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the U.N. trade embargo imposed on Iraq
since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait would be lifted as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Gaydali was here to attend the 12th session of the Iraqi-Turkish
Joint Committee for Trade, Economic and Technological Cooperation.
The last session was held in Baghdad in April, 1997.
</P>
<P>
During his seven-day visit, Gaydali will discuss with Iraqi
officials ways of strengthening cooperation, said INA.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, the Turkish minister told INA that due to the 10-
year-old trade embargo, Turkey has lost 30 billion U.S. dollars in
trade with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraq and Turkey have not been able to implement a
deal signed in 1997, under which a 1,100-kilometer-long pipeline
worth 2 billion dollars should be laid to transfer 10 billion cubic
meters of Iraqi gas to Turkey annually.
</P>
<P>
During the previous six phases of the oil-for-food program,
Turkish companies got 477 million dollars worth of contracts to
provide Iraq with detergents, medical appliances, equipment and
various spare parts, and ranked the ninth largest exporter to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, political relations have remained cool between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long criticized Turkey for allowing the United States
and British war planes to use its bases to patrol the northern no-
fly zone set up after the 1991 Gulf War with the so-called aim of
preventing Iraqi government troops from attacking the Kurds in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has never recognized the two no-fly zones, the other one in
southern Iraq set up by the U.S.-led western allies allegedly to
protect the Shiite Muslims, as they were not authorized by the U.N.
Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
