<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 Million Nigerians Suffer From River Blindness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- About 17 million Nigerians have
been affected with river blindness or onchocerciasis, with more
than 39 million others in the country facing the risk of
contacting the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics available here on Sunday, one third of
the world' s river blindness are in Nigerian.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has recently launched a mass campaign, 2000 National
Onchocerciasis Week, nationwide to carry out advocacy awareness
and enlightenment on the dangers and treatment of the disease.
</P>
<P>
An effective new drug, known as ivermectin, would be used on a
mass scale treatment of the disease in the affected communities
throughout the country, an official from the country's health
department was quoted as saying by local media.
</P>
<P>
He said the drugs would be given free of charge to all infected
people in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that river blindness is spread through exposure
to bites by the black fly called similum, whose breeding period
last between three to five years before manifestation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
