<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Occupational Disease: Biggest Health Threat to Chinese Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Occupational diseases have
become the biggest threat to workers' health as well as the
leading cause of early retirement due to disability, according to
the Ministry of Health (MOH).
</P>
<P>
A MOH official today warned that the development boom of
private and township enterprises would make the situation even
worse because the general job safety requirements are often
limited in those enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"It's very common in some areas that plant owners sacrifice
workers' health for making more money," Vice Health Minister Yin
Dakui said, though he stressed that most State-owned enterprises
have effectively controlled occupational hazards.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics from the MOH showed that pneumoconiosis
or black lung, a deadly illness occurring among miners, has preyed
upon at least 420,000 workers and killed about 130,000. About 15,
000 to 20,000 new cases are reported each year.
</P>
<P>
Accidental poisoning commonly reported in shoe-making and
garment factories was another leading killer, claiming several
hundred lives every year, Yin said.
</P>
<P>
He urged some 30,000 professionals involved in supervision and
prevention of occupational hazards to enhance their law
enforcement in their work.
</P>
<P>
The country's highest legislative body will discuss a draft law
on prevention of occupational disease, giving laborers a more
powerful legal weapon for protecting their health, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Old Kai Tak Airport In New Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A huge commercial cum office
complex has gradually emerged at Kai Tak, Hong Kong's old airport
that was finally closed in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
To date, about 20,000 square meters in the former Passenger
Terminal Building has been let out by the Government Property
Agency (GPA) to the private sector, bringing in an annual revenue
of about 13 million HK dollars (1.67 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Eight government departments have taken up office space at Kai
Tak, making it possible to save another 24 million HK dollars (3.
08 million U.S. dollars) a year in rental expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Since Kai Tak was vacated, this huge area has been under GPA's
management.
</P>
<P>
"Managing Kai Tak and putting it to good use is a new challenge
to us. It is such a vast place, covering some 246 hectares," said
Albert Lai Kwok-ying, a government property administrator.
</P>
<P>
"The land and hangars located to the northwest were required
for new development right away. The runway, the main apron areas
and the Passenger Terminal Building are not required for
development immediately. These have to be put to positive
temporary uses."
</P>
<P>
The Territory Development Department has been carrying out
decontamination and other jobs to pave the way to new housing. The
Lands Department looks after the land involved and has turned part
of the runway into a golf driving range.
</P>
<P>
"We have been trying to make use of these premises for
government offices or commercial purposes, as far as possible,"
Lai explained.
</P>
<P>
The former departure hall in the Passenger Terminal Building
now accommodates Hong Kong's largest bowling center and a car show.
</P>
<P>
The bowling center, which is now in trial operation, is
situated in the middle of the hall. The car show is adjacent. Both
are operated by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Part of the former hangar of the Government Flying Service (GFS)
is rented to a private helicopter company to do maintenance and
repairing.
</P>
<P>
"We are like a middleman, matching suitable users with
available properties with the aim of deriving the greatest
possible benefits from the former airport before its ultimate
redevelopment," Lai stressed.
</P>
<P>
The airport site will be redeveloped around 2004. By that time,
Kai Tak will have another new face. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
