<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hijacked Afghan Plane Passengers to Be Deported From London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Almost all the 79 remaining
passengers of the hijacked Afghan plane, which landed at a London
airport earlier this month, are to be deported after their
applications for asylum were found to be bogus.
</P>
<P>
The British government will make such an announcement within
the next two days, The Sunday Telegraph newspaper said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
That decision is expected to meet protests from refugee
organizations and is certain to face legal challenges which will
prolong the passengers' stay in Britain for at least another month,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
But a Home Office official said that Home Secretary Jack Straw
might be seen to be encouraging hijacking if he allowed the 79
passengers to stay.
</P>
<P>
It was suspected that some of the passengers were involved in
the hijack, as many of them were carrying an unusually large
amount of luggage for what was ostensibly an internal flight.
</P>
<P>
An Afghanistan Ariana Boeing 727 plane was forced to fly to
London's Stansted airport on February 7. The hijack later ended
peacefully when the hijackers surrendered after a four-day stand-
off.
</P>
<P>
A total of 37 men, 14 women and 28 children under 16 asked for
asylum following the hijack, claiming that they would face
persecution if they were sent back to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen people have appeared in a court, charged with
hijacking the plane and seventy-two others have already flown back
to Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
