<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Deputy Energy Minister Reza Ardakan on
Saturday voiced Tehran's readiness to provide the Gulf states with
more than 2 billion cubic meters of fresh water, the Islamic
Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with officials of the World Water Council on the
sidelines of the "Water Security in the Arab World" conference in
Cairo, Ardakan also expressed Iran's interest in the transfer of
the experiences to other regional states, the Muslim countries in
particular.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Production of aluminum ingots during the current
Iranian year (ending on March 20) reached 138,000 tons, a four-fold
increase compared to 1980, the English-language Iran Daily reported
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This figure is expected to increase to 350,000 tons by the end
of the Third Economic Development Plan (2000-2005), an official
from the Mines and Metals Ministry was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Production of aluminum ingots in 1997 and 1998 was 95,000 tons
and 124,000 tons respectively.
</P>
<P>
The official added that a new aluminum production unit with an
annual production capacity of 280,000 tons is in the final stages
and will go on stream next year.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran has earned 600 million U.S. dollars from exports
of hand-woven carpets since the beginning of the current Iranian
calendar year, IRNA reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of Iran Handcrafts Organization Abdulhamid
Khalili said Saturday night in Kermanshah, western Kermanshah
province, that the exports showed an increase of 68 percent
compared to the same period last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
Khalili believed that the country's exports of hand-woven
carpets would reach 700 million dollars by the end of the current
Iranian year, adding that at present some 5 million people
throughout the country are professionally involved in carpet-
weaving industry.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey-Iraq Joint Economic Commission (JEC) will
convene in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad after a four-year interval,
the Anatolia News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish delegation is in Iraq to discuss ways to revitalize
the commercial relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between Turkey and Iraq reached 3 billion dollars
before the 1990 Gulf Crisis caused by Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. The
figure dropped to 100 million dollars due to the United Nations
embargo on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
