<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac: France's Mideast Policy Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Apparently trying to ward off
the controversy caused by Prime Minister Lionel Jospin's remarks
in the Middle East, French President Jacques Chirac has stressed
that his country's Middle East policy remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the clarification in a telephone conversation with
Jospin on Saturday night after Jospin said in Jerusalem on
Thursday that the attacks by Hezbollah guerrillas on Israeli
occupation troops in southern Lebanon were "terrorist acts".
</P>
<P>
In the telephone conversation, Chirac said that France's
attitude toward Israel and Arab countries should be one of "
impartiality", said a communique released by the Elysee
presidential palace on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
"The head of state has reaffirmed the consistency of the
foreign policy of France and the balance which inspires the action
of our country in the Middle East," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
Jospin's comment sparked fury among Arab countries and violent
protests ensued when he visited the University of Bir Zeit in the
Palestine-controlled West Bank on Saturday. Angry Palestinian
students threw stones at the French prime minister and jumped on
his bullet-proof Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
The incident caused Jospin to cancel a scheduled visit to a
Palestinian refugee camp and a planned news conference at the end
of his three-day visit to Israel and the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Besides the diplomatic embarrassments in the Middle East,
Jospin's controversial remarks also ruffled up political feathers
in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Right-wing politicians and the French press accused the
socialist prime minister of damaging France's image abroad by
trying to score political points against Chirac in the run up to
their battle for the French presidency in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Members of the socialist, green and communist parties defended
Jospin.
</P>
<P>
"This is disastrous for France's image. The prime minister has
made a serious slip," former right-wing prime minister Alain Juppe
told France 3 television.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Edouard Balladur, who shared power with
socialist President Francois Mitterrand from 1993 to 1995, told
LCI television it is vital for France to speak with one voice,
especially as France is taking over the rotating presidency of the
15-nation European Union in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
