<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-Japan Trade Expected to Rise: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The two-way trade between
China and Japan is expected to continue its growth this year, the
China Daily Business Weekly reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Trade expert Xu Changwen told the weekly that he expects the
Sino-Japanese trade to reach 70 billion U.S. dollars this year, as
compared to 66.17 billion US dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Japan remained China's largest trading partner for seven
consecutive years last year. Both imports and exports recorded a
record high last year with China's imports from Japan jumping 19.4
percent to 33.77 billion U.S. dollars, and exports to Japan grew 9.
2 percent to hit 32.4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The strong trade growth indicates that the two-way trade has
recovered from the impact of the Asian financial crisis which
drove the Sino-Japanese trade volume down to 57.9 billion U.S.
dollars in 1998 from 60.8 billion U.S. dollars in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the growth to the fast economic growth in
China and the recovery of Japanese economy as well as a strong
Japanese yen and a stable Chinese renminbi.
</P>
<P>
The expert said that he expects both Chinese and Japanese
economies to perform better this year, which will further fuel the
development of bilateral trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Health Contracts Blocked by U.S., Britain: Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Health Minister Umid
Medhat Mubarak accused the United States and Britain of blocking
medical contracts Iraq signed with foreign companies under the oil-
for-food program, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to INA, Mubarak said the U.S. and British
delegates at the United Nations Sanctions Committee put on hold 15
health contracts last month.
</P>
<P>
The minister condemned that the conduct of Washington and London
represented "a war of genocide against the entire population of
Iraq and all peace-loving nations."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long accused the U.S. and Britain of impeding the
implementation of the oil-for-food deal by deliberately blocking
the approval of its contracts for purchasing humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
Under the humanitarian program now in its seventh phase, Iraq is
allowed to sell limited amount of oil and use the revenues, under
U.N. supervision, to buy humanitarian goods for its people, who are
suffering from the decade-old sanctions imposed on the country in
1990 following its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by Iraq's health ministry
recently, some 1.27 million children and elderly people died as a
result of the continuation of the sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
