<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
Saturday condemned the students who threw stones at and wounded
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin at Birzeit University as "
forces of darkness," and shut down the campus for three days.
</P>
<P>
Several students were arrested and will be prosecuted, West Bank
Preventive Security Service chief Jibril Rajoub told the Jerusalem
Post.
</P>
<P>
Jospin and his entourage were assaulted as they left an
auditorium of the hilltop campus near Ramallah following his speech
to students. The assailants were apparently protesting against
Jospin's calling Lebanese anti-Israel Hezbollah guerrillas as "
terrorists" in remarks last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Iran has provided Lebanon with Fajr rockets with a firing
range of up to 70 kilometers, putting Israel's Haifa bay area
within range of a direct hit from Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
The missiles have not been supplied to Lebanese Hezbollah
guerrillas, but are being maintained by Iranian militants stationed
in Lebanon as a strategic reserve in case of intensified military
conflict with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The reality now facing Israel is that in the case of a
confrontation in which Fajr missiles are used, hundreds of
thousands of people living in the north of Israel, and not just
areas along the international border between Israel and Lebanon,
will have to seek refuge in bomb shelters.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel Defense Force is drawing a plan for withdrawal from
the Israeli-occupied buffer zone in South Lebanon unilaterally,
instead of seeking a withdrawal with peace agreement between
Israel, Lebanon and Syria, the major foreign power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak ordered the change. Barak
promised to bring Israel soldiers in the zone back home by July 7
this year. However, he had stressed several times in the past that
he believes negotiations with Beirut and Damascus will result in
peace agreements by then.
</P>
<P>
Barak is to summon his cabinet on Sunday to discuss the
situation in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- During the weekend fighting between IDF and Hezbollah, Israel
Air Force was given permission to attack targets less than 100
meters away from a Lebanese civilian village.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time IDF implemented the new policy adopted by
the inner-circle security cabinet 10 days ago, which permitted IDF
to retaliate Hezbollah guerrillas hidden near populated areas.
</P>
<P>
These decisions, which will possibly cause great civilian
casualties, had earned severe criticisms from Arab countries and
even the United States, the major patron of Israel in the world
politics arena. 
</P>
