<HEADLINE> Zanzibar President Not Allowed to Run For Third Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's ruling party
Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) Saturday rejected proposals to amend the
Zanzibar constitution seeking to allow President Salmin Amour, a
CCM member, to run for an unprecedented third term, local media
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The CCM National Executive Committee (NEC), at the end of a
session in Tanzania's central city of Dodoma, resolved that
discussion on the possibility of amending the Zanzibar
constitution to allow for a third term of presidency will be done
after the forthcoming general elections slated for October.
</P>
<P>
The NEC has resolved to postpone discussions on proposals to
amend the Zanzibar constitution until some time after the
elections, CCM Secretary General Philip Mangula was quoted by the
Sunday Observer newspaper as saying after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
This means that Salmin is automatically disqualified from
running in this year's Zanzibar presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The NEC resolution came two days after heated debate by the
Central Committee of the NEC of CCM meeting here behind closed
doors from Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar joined with mainland Tanganyika to form the United
Republic of Tanzania after a revolt in 1964 that ousted the sultan
and Omani Arabs who ruled the island.
</P>
<P>
It is a semiautonomous state with its own government and
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Salmin became Zanzibar President in 1990. He was reelected in
1995 after claiming a narrow victory over the opposition Civic
United Front party, which accused the then ruling CCM party of
rigging the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
