<HEADLINE> Tanzania, EU Trade Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's trade with
the European Union (EU) has been declining over the past 25 years
despite of the preferential trade instruments provided by the EU,
the Sunday Observer newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a EU-ACP (African, Caribbean and Pacific)
trade report as saying that Tanzania's exports to the EU market
declined from 52.9 percent of its total exports in 1991 to 36.9
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Tanzania's imports from the EU, which stood
at 31.3 percent in 1991, declined to 30.8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to EU Economic Councilor for Tanzania Klaus Schmidt,
in 1990, the trade balance between Tanzania and the EU stood at
222.696 million euros while in 1998, this figure slumped to 62.899
million euros.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as saying that the imports from the EU to
Tanzania, which stood at 399.644 million euros in 1990, dropped to
312.685 million euros in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The leading exports of Tanzania included coffee, fish fillets
and unprocessed tobacco, while the leading imports included
second-hand clothing, machinery, engine parts, petroleum and oil
products, cars and other vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
