<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caucasus Pact Initiative to Be Discussed in Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The framework of a proposed
Caucasus stability pact will be discussed in Tbilisi early in
March, Turkish press reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the United Nations, the United States, Russia,
Turkey, Azerbaijan, Georgia and Armenia will gather in the Georgian
capital for discussions.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first concrete move on the proposal since it
was raised by Turkish President Suleyman Demirel during his
official visit to Georgia last month.
</P>
<P>
"A stability pact for the Caucasus region has to be worked out,
as it was for the Balkans," Demirel told a press conference jointly
held with his Georgian counterpart Eduard Shevardnadze in Tbilisi
on January 16.
</P>
<P>
"Stability and peace in Caucasus should be under European
guarantee because this is important not not only for Georgia and
other countries of this region, but for their neighbors," he added.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Demirel, Shevardnadze termed the proposal as a very
important and historic one that could bring long-awaited peace to
the region.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified official close to the Turkish government was
quoted as saying that Turkey, neighboring the Caucasus region,
insists on the establishment of such a pact in order to secure the
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, Dr. Emin Gurses from University of Sakarya in western
Turkey said "The Caucasus pact is actually planned by the United
States, and Turkey is just an instrument."
</P>
<P>
"If you ask why the United States is playing a key role in
establishing the pact, I can tell you that the region has great
amount of oil and natural gas resources. The United States does not
want trouble in the Caucasus," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov is
scheduled to pay a two-day official visit to Turkey starting on
February 28.
</P>
<P>
A diplomatic source told Turkish press that Klebanov, as a
special envoy of Russian acting President Vladimir Putin, would
bring Demirel a letter from Putin with regard to the suggestion of
Caucasus stability pact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
