<HEADLINE> Mugabe Strengthens Control Over Energy Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe announced that his office has taken over the Ministry of
Transport and Energy following the resignation of Minister Enos
Chikowore on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe made this announcement on Saturday night in an
interview with the Sunday Mail newspaper at the Manyame Airbase
following his tour of areas hit by floods in Chiredzi and
Beitbridge of southern Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"I have accepted Minister Chilowore's resignation and the
ministry will for now work in our office," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we will continue to work on the fuel situation
and try to rectify the problem."
</P>
<P>
The country has been facing a serious fuel shortage since
December last year because of shortage of foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
"My view is that we should not just resolve the problem in an
ad hoc way. What we must ensure is that we have adequate fuel for
a long period and on a permanent basis," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would soon negotiate with a "friendly
country" for an arrangement to fill the strategic tanks. But he
did not specify which country, earlier reports said that South
Africa would most likely come into its help.
</P>
<P>
The solution is not in getting one or two ships bringing in
fuel or getting new lines of credit, he said, stressing that "we
have to have an assurance on fuel supplies."
</P>
<P>
Commenting oZimbabweans who have been displaced.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Protection Unit is now in control of the situation,
with all the troubled spots having been identified and measures
being put in place to provide distressed villagers with food,
shelter, blankets and clothes, he said.
</P>
<P>
The national death toll due to Cyclone Eline has risen to 29
and 250, 000 people have been left homeless in heavy rains.
</P>
</TEXT>
