<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Global Oil Price Posts Pressures on Chinese Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Increases in prices of
petroleum products on the world market are threatening the
security of China's oil supply, which has prompted an urgent
adjustment of the country's energy strategy, reported today's
China's Daily.
</P>
<P>
The paper's Business Weekly said in a front-page report that
the dramatic fluctuations in international crude oil prices
negatively affected China because the country has become
increasingly dependent on imported oil since 1993.
</P>
<P>
It quoted an industry official as saying that China can not
accept endlessly rising oil prices on the world market.
</P>
<P>
The country imported nearly 40 million tons of crude oil and
oil products last year, or 20 percent of the country's total
consumption, the paper quoted Chen Geng, deputy director of the
Station Administration of Petroleum and Chemical Industries, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The demand for crude oil is expected to grow at an annual rate
of 4 percent during the 21st century. It expects to import 42
million tons of crude oil this year.
</P>
<P>
China plans to develop other energy resources, such as natural
gas and hydropower to augment or replace its use of crude oil, the
paper noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
