<HEADLINE> Manila Determined to Increase Software Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is determined
to increase its exports from 300 million U.S. dollars in 1999 to a
hefty 1 billion dollars in the next five years, said a senior
official Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here by the presidential office,
Secretary Filemon Uriarte of the Department of Science and
Technology (DOST) said this is through the implementation of the
200 million peso (5 million dollar) Virtual Center for Technology
Innovation in Information Technology (VCTI).
</P>
<P>
The country's export rose to 35 billion dollars last year,
buoying hopes that the government could hit its targeted export
value of 50 billion dollars in the year 2004, he said.
</P>
<P>
"DOST has decided to prioritize information technology (IT)
because this sector, particularly software development, has high
added value that caters to a large potential market requiring
minimal capital investment," Uriarte said.
</P>
<P>
He said the project was also designed to spur electronic
commerce development in the Philippines, which has been hobbled by
the absence of a payment backbone and a legal framework to tackle
such legal issues as intellectual property rights and consumer
protection.
</P>
<P>
Uriarte said with the implementation of VCTI, the Philippines
hopes to capture a substantial portion in the global markets for
local IT products and services.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to produce at least 5,000 certified IT
professionals in the next five years to spearhead software into
the 1 billion dollar level, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
