<HEADLINE> Hornets Mason Arrested, Charged with Third-Degree Assault </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Charlotte Hornets forward
Anthony Mason was arrested and charged with third-degree assault
after an altercation this morning outside a bar in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
According to a police spokesman, Mason and four other men were
involved in a fight with three other men this morning at a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
The three men allegedly assaulted by Mason's group were
hospitalized with minor injuries. According to police, Mason was
not injured in the fight.
</P>
<P>
Mason rejoined the Hornets early in the second quarter of
tonight's game against the New Jersey Nets. It was unclear whether
Mason was arraigned, released or posted bail.
</P>
<P>
Mason, 33, played five years with the New York Knicks before
being traded to Charlotte in July 1996. He was arrested in New
York during All-Star Weekend in 1998 on a statutory rape charge.
</P>
<P>
He later agreed to a plea bargain in which the more serious
charges were dropped and was sentenced to 200 hours of community
service.
</P>
<P>
Mason is averaging 10.7 points, a team-leading 8.2 rebounds and
4.1 assists in 53 games for the Hornets this season.
</P>
<P>
Mason helped the Knicks reach the NBA Finals in 1994 and led
the NBA in minutes played in the 1995-96 season. He was traded to
the Hornets forward Larry Johnson. 
</P>
