<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, February 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia, the world's top oil producer, has
pledged to raise oil production to help rein in the buoyant oil
prices in the world oil market.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia made the promise in a joint statement issued with
visiting U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson Saturday. But the
statement did not give detailed output plans of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Richardson arrived here from Kuwait and his visit came in an
apparent attempt to convince Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, the two
major members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC), to help bring down the robust oil prices.
</P>
<P>
OPEC adopted a year-long policy last March to slash its member
states' oil output to prop up the sagging oil prices, which have
recently jumped to a nine-year high of nearly 29 U.S. dollars a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
OPEC ministers will meet on March 27 in Vienna to discuss the
current situation and future policies. Some consuming giants,
especially the U.S., want the oil producing states to pump more
oil to tame the oil prices. (Saudi Arabia-US-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China plans to increase its textile products export
to 60-65 billion U.S. dollars in 2005, up about 46 percent from
the current level, the China Daily Business Weekly reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Customs figures show that China exported 41.27 billion
U.S. dollars worth of textile products last year, up about 2.0
percent. The exports accounted for 21 percent of China's total
exports for that year.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted that the exports of textile products is
expected to reach 48 billion U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country will increase its fiber processing
capacity to 13 million tons in 2005 from the expected 10 million
tons in 2000, the paper quoted the State Administration of Textile
Industry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Du Yuzhou, director general of the administration, said China
will also strive to improve the quality of its textile products.
(China-Textile Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- The German government said Thursday it hopes its
candidate Caio Koch-Weser will succeed in getting the position of
the managing director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
despite the candidates from Japan and the United States compete
with him for the job.
</P>
<P>
A Finance Ministry spokeswoman said that Germany hoped Deputy
Finance Minister Caio Koch-Weser would get the formal support from
the European Union finance ministers at their meeting next Monday.
</P>
<P>
There was a conflict between Germany and France about the
nomination of the managing director of IMF. The United States has
pledged to support the European candidate and Germany hoped the U.
S. would insist on supporting the German candidate.
</P>
<P>
55-year-old Caio Koch-Weser had been a top official at the
World Bank for many years, but the U.S. has questioned his
qualification for the job as head of the IMF and some Washington
officials were questioning whether Koch-Weser was able to lead
much larger IMF. (Germany-IMF-Head) 
</P>
</TEXT>
