<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Diplomat Expelled to Canada for Flight to Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. authorities Saturday
expelled a Cuban diplomat ignoring an expulsion order and put him
on a flight bound for Montreal, Canada, where he will be flown to
Cuba's capital of Havana.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat, Jose Imperatori, earlier Saturday announced he
went on a hunger strike to protest the U.S. expulsion order.
</P>
<P>
"The diplomat in question no longer enjoys the privileges and
immunities conferred by the Vienna Convention on Diplomatic
Relations," the U.S. State Department said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
"He has been expelled from the United States for not
voluntarily departing by the appointed time," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department announced last week Imperatori should
leave the United States by 1:30 p.m. Saturday and his diplomatic
privileges and immunities will be removed after the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference just before the deadline,
Imperatori said he would clear his name of allegations that he was
a contact of a U.S. immigration official charged with spying for
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"I have become the victim of a major slander. I have been
wrongly accused of doing intelligence work in the United States,"
he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Imperatori said he resigned his post as consular officer at 7 a.
m. Saturday, thus voluntarily eliminating his immunity six hours
before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
"I shall remain in the same apartment where I have lived, and
as of this moment I declare myself in a hunger strike until I have
been absolutely cleared of the accusation brought against me," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The State Department announced earlier this week that
Imperatori may be arrested if he failed to leave the country by
the U.S. deadline.
</P>
<P>
"I shall not resist arrest, not even if I am handcuffed and
jailed. My morale and my truth will be my shield," Imperatori
said.
</P>
<P>
Hours after the deadline, agents from the Federal Bureau of
Investigation went to his apartment in Maryland and drove him to
the Ronald Reagan National Airport.
</P>
<P>
Imperatori said that Cuban Interests Section officials have
been "categorically and precisely instructed not to do
intelligence work in the United States" since the mission was
opened 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Such instructions have been strictly observed and with
absolutely no exceptions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department declared Imperatori "Persona Non
Grata" after FBI concluded he was the Washington contact for
Mariano M. Faget, a Miami-based official of the U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service (INS). Faget was arrested a week ago
on charges of spying for Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban government said that the expulsion is nothing but a
maneuver to block the return of six-year-old Elian Gonzalez, who
was rescued in the sea off Florida after his mother drowned when
their boat capsized.
</P>
<P>
The father of Gonzalez, backed by the Cuban government, asked
the boy to return to him. INS ruled the boy belongs to his father
and should be returned.
</P>
<P>
But the boy's relatives, supported by Cuban exiles and anti-
Cuba congressmen, insisted Gonzalez stay in the United States.
The boy still remain in Florida with his relatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
