<HEADLINE> Cuban Diplomat Taken From Home to Airport by FBI Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Former Cuban diplomat Jose
Imperatori, who the United States accused of espionage, was
detained by a group of FBI agents and taken away from his home to
an airport late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
His lawyer, former Baltimore mayor Kurt Schmoke, told reporters
at the scene that Imperatori was being taken "straight to the
airport."
</P>
<P>
In protest of the U.S. accusations, Imperatori, 46, resigned
from his post as vice-consul early Saturday at the Cuban Interests
Section here, thus losing his diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government had already declared him "persona non grata
" and given him until 1:30 p.m. (1830 GMT) to leave the United
States. Officials had said that after that time he would forfeit
his diplomatic immunity and could therefore face criminal charges
or deportation. 
</P>
