<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights
of today's major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
All major Beijing-Based newspaper today gave their front-page
coverage to China's top legislator Li Peng's tour to Jiangsu and
Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao's inspection to Sichuan,
mobilizing the "Three Emphases" education drive.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, Chairman of the Standing Committee of China's National
People's Congress, stressed the importance of "Three Emphases"
education during his inspection tour in east China's Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
Hu, also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (
CPC), made the call during his eight-day inspection tour of
southwest China's Sichuan Province from February 19 to 26.
</P>
<P>
He has called for earnestly conducting the "Three Emphases"
education among county officials and taking advantage of the
national drive to develop western China to speed up the economic
development of Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
His tour is part of the recent CPC Central Committee program to
promote "Three Emphasizes" education, which stresses on
theoretical study, political awareness and good conduct among city
and county officials across the nation.
</P>
<P>
People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese Ministry of Health announced that no epidemic
diseases have occurred since devastating floods hit the country in
1998, thanks to the great efforts made by public health workers.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that epidemic diseases occur normally in the year
with major natural disasters or the following year, and the death
toll from these epidemics often exceed that from the disaster
itself. It is a rarity that no major epidemic has occurred in
China since 1998, they said.
</P>
<P>
 Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji met here Saturday with Japanese
Environment Agency Director-general Kayoko Shimizu and Environment
Minister of Republic of Korea Kim Myung-Ja.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese and ROK guests are here to attend the on-going
Meeting of China, Japan and ROK Environment Ministers held in
Beijing. The tri-party convention held its first meeting in Seoul
in January, 1999.
</P>
<P>
 China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- The newspaper's Business Weekly carried a front-page story
today on the adjustment of China's oil exploration and refining
industry under the pressure of hiking global oil price.
</P>
<P>
It said that increases in prices of petroleum products on the
world market are threatening the security of China's oil supply.
The threat has prompted an urgent adjustment of the country's
energy strategy.
</P>
<P>
-- A growing number of Chinese enterprises either have or will
establish processing plants in foreign countries, the newspaper
said today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation indicate 50 overseas processing trade projects,
involving 258 million U.S. dollars in input from Chinese investors,
were established in 1999, the paper noted. 
</P>
