<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Privately-Owned Firearms Quintupled in 7 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The number of privately
owned weapons in Argentina has almost quintupled from 400,000 in
1993 to 1.938 million, authorities said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The National Weapons Registry (RENAR) said in its latest report
that 60 percent of all of the weapons registered are privately
owned, 25 percent are controlled by members of the armed forces
and security agencies, and the rest are used by employees of
security firms or are kept by collectors.
</P>
<P>
RENAR said that an average of 4,500 pieces of new weapons are
sold every month to registered users, while a much larger number
of weapons are estimated to be sold in the black market in the
country. As a result, only four percent of the weapons used in
crimes are registered.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine government is planning to launch a project to
diminish the number of privately owned weapons by collecting them
from private owners and giving out commodities as compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
