<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Chinese Science News (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese zoologists believe that frequent sightings of traces
left by wild South China tigers in the past two years prove that
the most endangered tiger species is able to exist in the wild.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of four tiger pawprints in the Heishan Mountain
Reserve in central China's Hunan Province earlier this year has
been confirmed by Deng Xuejian, a senior South China tiger
research expert with Hunan Teacher's University. The prints were
preserved intact under a block of crusted snow.
</P>
<P>
Ancient City Unearthed in northeast China
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists recently discovered a 4,000-year-old
city site on the outskirts of Lianyungang, a coastal city in east
China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The site covers a total area of about 150,000 sq. m, including
41,000 sq. m for the city proper.
</P>
<P>
South China Tigers Spotted in Wilderness
</P>
<P>
South China Tigers, one of the most endangered species in the
world, have been spotted in the mountainous regions of Zhejiang, a
coastal province in east China.
</P>
<P>
The Zhejiang Provincial Administration of Forestry and the
Baishanzu Natural Reserve released the news at a press conference
today.
</P>
<P>
Innovative Technology Vital to China's Economy in 21st Century
</P>
<P>
American Chinese Chang-Lin Tien, a member of the U.S. National
Science Board, said in Beijing over the weekend that the
application of innovative technology is vital to China's fast
economic development in the new century.
</P>
<P>
The 7th Berkeley Chancellor of the University of California
made these remarks at a symposium for Chinese youth in the 21st
century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
