<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bayern Munich Beats Frankfurt 4-1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Forward Reichenberger scored Frankfurt's only goal in the 49th
minute.
</P>
<P>
Munich has now won four and drawn one since the winter break
and appears in top form as it resumes its pursuit of three titles
Wednesday against Real Madrid in the Champions Cup.
</P>
<P>
Munich stayed five points clear of Bayer Leverkusen, which also
appeared inspired by the balmy temperatures to run over Hertha
Berlin, the league's other Champions Cup team. It won in a 3-1
rout,while lining up four strikers.
</P>
<P>
Third-place Hamburger SV, eight points behind, beat
Kaiserslautern 2-1 despite having a player sent off the field with
a red card as its scoring goalie, Hans-Joerg Butt converted his
ninth penalty. That left him one behind the league's top marksman.
</P>
<P>
Leverkusen seized on Berlin's shaky defense and led 3-1 by the
half on goals by Ulf Kirsten, Ze Roberto and Paulo Rink.
</P>
<P>
Midfielder Stefan Beinlich was at the center of most of
Leverkusen's goals, after his team was shocked by Marco Rehmer's
ninth-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
Beinlich, who will join Berlin next season, sent a low cross
into the box in the 13th minute which a diving Kirsten, feet-first,
drove into the net. His hard shot in the 28th was fisted away, but
Rink followed through for the 3-1.
</P>
<P>
Bremen also got a 83rd minute goal from Peruvian forward
Claudio Pizzaro to earn a 2-2 draw with Wolfsburg and Stuttgart
finally won 3-1 against Duisburg. On Friday, Rostock and Freiburg
drew 1-1 in a relegation battle.
</P>
<P>
Stuttgart snapped a four-match losing streak, behind 26th and
43rd minute goals from Bulgarian Krassimir Balakov, once the team'
s star but now in danger of losing his starting role. A late score
came from Sean Dundee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
