<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Shatters European Record to Win Heptathlon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENT, Belgium, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Tomas Dvorak not only
led a Czech one-two in the men's heptathlon at the European indoor
athletic championships but also set up a continental record en
route to winning the event on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Czech heptathlete, twice world champion and world record
holder for the 10-event decathlon, garnered 6,424 points from the
two-day seven-event competition, beating the eight-year-old
previous European mark of 6,418 points held by Frenchman Christian
Plaziat.
</P>
<P>
He ran a 6.92-second 60 meters, long jumped 7.81 meters, shot
put 16.82 meters, cleared 2.04 meters on the high jump, clocked 7.
78 seconds over the 60-meter hurdles, pole vaulted 5.00 meters and
was timed 2:45.68 for the 1,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Dvorak's shot put distance was more than two meters further
than the previous record holder's 14.53 meters.
</P>
<P>
The Czech grip on the heptathlon title was more than secured
when Dvorak's teammate Roman Sebrle finished runner-up with 6,271
points, 71 points ahead of Estonia's Erki Nool who got the bronze
medal.
</P>
<P>
Muriel Hurtis of France won the women's 200-meter race with a
clocking of 23.06 seconds while compatriot and pre-race favorite
Fabe Dia finished a distant sixth and last at 24.38 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Kajsa Bergqvist got Sweden a sweet gold medal by winning the
women's high jump event with a clearance of 2.00 meters, followed
by Zuzana Hlavonova of the Czech Republic and Olga Kaliturina of
Russia on 1.98 and 1.96 meters respectively.
</P>
<P>
Romania also got on to the gold medal chart on Saturday as
Violeta Szekely won the women's 1,500-meter race with a timing of
four minutes 12.82 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Russia, the past medal grabbers at the European championships,
got its first gold medal of the current championships by winning
the women's triple jump event.
</P>
<P>
Tatyana Lebedeva hit 14.68 meters on her second outing of the
day and skipped her last two outings altogether to take the gold
medal for Russia.
</P>
<P>
Cristina Nicolau of Romania jumped 14.63 meters on her first
outing to clinch the silver medal while Iva Prandzheva of Bulgaria
did not come within medal range until her final outing when she
cleared an identical 14.63 meters only for the bronze.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian fouled four times and jumped 14.26 meters on her
good jump on the fourth outing.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Stevens entertained a Saturday turnout of local crowds
by clinching the host country Belgium's lone medal so far as he
finished runner-up in between two Britons in the men's 200-meter
finals.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian clocked 20.70 seconds for the silver while
Christian Malcolm, the pre-race favorite, lived up to his
expectation by winning the event with a clocking of 20.54 econds.
</P>
<P>
Russia got its second gold at the Gent European championships
as Larisa Peleshenko shot put 20.15 meters to win the women's
title while France also hit a second gold medal when Linda Ferga
led a French one-two finish in the 60-meter hurdles with a
clocking of 7.88 seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Indoor Athletic Championship Results (7)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENT, Belgium, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Following are results
for the 26th European indoor track and field championships held
here on Saturday:
</P>
