<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Struggles to Draw with Wimbledon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Andy Cole scored a late goal to
help champions Manchester United for a 2-2 draw with Wimbledon in
a English premier league match on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United, which is standing at the leading place in
the premier league standings, twice came from behind for the tie.
</P>
<P>
Cole's precise, low shot 10 minutes from time after a brilliant
run by Ryan Giggs kept the European champions six points clear of
Leeds United as they prepare for a hectic return to Champions
League action next week.
</P>
<P>
Leeds were held 0-0 at Middlesbrough, who had Italian Gianluca
Festa sent off four minutes from time, after dominating their
match and having a goal disallowed.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal regained third place, ahead of inactive Liverpool on
goal difference, by beating Glenn Hoddle's Southampton 3-1 in the
former England manager's first defeat at the club.
</P>
<P>
United have 57 points, Leeds 51 and Arsenal 47.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United recalled David Beckham, dropped last weekend
after a training ground clash with manager Alex Ferguson, but a
lively and determined Wimbledon looked to have eclipsed his return
until Cole struck.
</P>
<P>
Jason Euell put Wimbledon ahead after just one minute,taking
advantage of defensive confusion to volley past Australian Mark
Bosnich in goal.
</P>
<P>
With Dwight Yorke on international duty and captain Roy Keane
and Paul Scholes both suspended, United looked to Dutchman Jordi
Cruyff and he scored on the half hour.
</P>
<P>
Carl Cort rocked United again in the 62nd minute when his soft-
looking header slipped past the flailing Bosnich and Wimbledon
then had a torrid time before Cole scored.
</P>
<P>
Jon Harley scored his first goal and the winner for fifth-
placed Chelsea, who beat league tail-enders Watford 2-1.
</P>
<P>
West Ham's fiery Italian striker Paolo di Canio failed a
fitness test and avoided an encounter with referee Paul Alcock,the
official he infamously pushed to the ground in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Hammers lost 4-0 to Everton, Nicky Barmby scoring the first
hat-trick of his career.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle United, who beat Sheffield Wednesday 8-0 in September,
won 2-0 at Hillsborough in a match likely to cement Wednesday's
relegation.
</P>
<P>
England captain Alan Shearer scored and took his tally against
Wednesday to six in the two games.
</P>
<P>
"Six goals. It's not often you see that in a season, scoring
six against one side," he said. "I'm delighted but I'm more
delighted with the three points."
</P>
<P>
A minute's silence was held before Saturday's matches as a mark
of respect for Sir Stanley Matthews, the great England winger who
died on Wednesday at the age of 85. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
