<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Police Discover Hezbollah Arms Depot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkish police
on Sunday seized a major arsenal allegedly
belonging to the clandestine Islamic Hezbollah
group in southeast Turkey, the Anatolia News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Gaffar Okkan, police chief in the southeastern
provincial capital of Diyarbakir, disclosed that
the arsenal of rifles, pistols and silencers was
found in the southeastern town of Mardin.
</P>
<P>
The operation was part of the month-long
nationwide crackdown on the Hezbollah
organization, which has resulted in the unearthing
of 57 corpses and arrests of hundreds of suspects.
</P>
<P>
Okkan said that the search was conducted upon
confessions made by Edip Gumus and Cemal Tutar,
two hard-core members of Hezbollah who were
captured in earlier police raids.
</P>
<P>
"We have established from ballistics tests that
50 attacks involving killings and woundings
between the years 1992 and 1995 were carried out
in Diyarbakir with these weapons," Okkan said. "In
these attacks there were 36 deaths and 36
injuries."
</P>
<P>
The Turkey-based Hezbollah, which reportedly
has no links with the Lebanese Hezbollah group
that has been engaged in guerrilla war against
Israeli occupation troops in south Lebanon, seeks
to establish a fundamentalist regime in
constitutionally secular Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Its earliest victims in secret killings were
believed to be supporters of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), leading to suspicions that
the group was backed by the state. The Turkish
government has strongly denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Okkan admitted that Hezbollah members had
sometimes worn police and other official uniforms
during their attacks in and around Diyarbakir and
consequently "gave the image that the state had
been behind them."
</P>
<P>
As the PKK fell at a low ebb after its leader
Abdullah Ocalan's arrest last year, Hezbollah
emerged as a major anti-government secret body.
The fact that dozens of businessmen were reported
missing late last year has prompted police to
start a major crackdown on the group since January
17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
