<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2150GMT, Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A militiaman of the pro-Israeli South
Lebanon Army (SLA) was injured Sunday in a
roadside bomb attack by Lebanese guerrillas in the
Israeli-occupied zone in southern Lebanon,
security sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian- and Syrian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, has claimed responsibility for the
attack on the Khardaly bridge in the eastern
sector of the "security zone," which brought to 12
the number of SLA members wounded in the region
since the beginning of the year.(Lebanon-SLA-
Injured)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak held
talks with visiting Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on the latest developments in the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders met before noon Sunday at the
presidential palace, and Arafat briefed Mubarak on
the outcome of his recent meetings with U.S.
Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross and French Premier
Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
He also told Mubarak about latest developments
in peace talks with the Israeli side, but no
further details have been disclosed.(Egypt-
Palestine-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A leader of the Lebanese Hezbollah on
Sunday demanded that French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin apologize for branding guerrilla attacks
against Israeli occupation troops as "terrorist"
acts.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah Deputy Secretary General Sheikh Naem
Kassem said Jospin should make an apology if he
wants to visit Lebanon in the future since he has
become persona non grata for his "obvious insult
against the resistance movement and the Lebanese
people."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he acclaimed the demonstration
staged by Palestinian students during Jospin's
visit to the Birzeit University in the West Bank
city of Ramallah on Saturday. (Lebanon-Hezbollah-
Jospin Remarks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
said Sunday that U.S. President Bill Clinton wants
Israel and Syria reach a peace agreement by May,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks at a weekly cabinet
meeting, the first thorough cabinet debate of its
kind on Israel's Lebanon policy after the current
government came to power nearly eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
Barak also told his ministers that former prime
minister Yitzhak Rabin told Americans that Israel
will withdraw from the Golan Heights to the June
4, 1967 lines under certain conditions, which was
also the position of former prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's government. (Israel-Syria-
Deal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
admitted Sunday that there is no certainty that
Israel will reach a deal with Syria and Lebanon
before the promised deadline for Israeli troops
withdrawal from south Lebanon in July.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks at a special cabinet
session on Israel's Lebanon policy, which was the
first thorough cabinet debate on the issue since
the current government came to power nearly eight
months ago.
</P>
<P>
The ministers focused their debate on Barak's
proposal to bring Israeli soldiers based in the
Israeli-occupied buffer zone in south Lebanon back
home by July 7 "with or without an agreement" with
Lebanon and Syria, the main foreign power broker
in Lebanon, according to Israel Radio reports.
(Israel-Lebanon-Pullout) 
</P>
