<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demilitarization of Cyprus Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Turkish Cypriot community on Cyprus on Sunday expressed support for
the demilitarization of the island.
</P>
<P>
Izzet Izcan, general secretary of the Turkish Cypriot Patriotic
Movement, said on the sidelines of a bicommunal event, organized by
his Movement and the left-wing Greek Cypriot AKEL party, that "we
do not need an army on this island," including the British bases.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two communities on the island should be
security guarantors of each other and "that should be our target
and goal and we should work in that direction."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Cyprus "should be an independent and sovereign
state."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, AKEL parliamentary spokesman Andreas Christou urged
the Cyprus government to demand the termination of alleged
espionage activities by the British bases.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bases "have been established on our territory,
against the will of the people of Cyprus, Greek and Turkish
Cypriots, and continue to operate against the interests of the
people."
</P>
<P>
Recent press reports said that the British bases were using
their monitoring network to spy on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said one of the British-American ground
satellite monitoring stations, which tapped into the world's fax,
telephone and radio exchanges, is located within the British bases
on Cyprus, cueing a media frenzy about British "spying" activities
on the island.
</P>
<P>
Britain retains two military bases in Cyprus since granting the
island independence from colonial rule in 1960.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island following a failed
pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Students Stage More Protests Against French PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Palestinian students
on Sunday took to the streets in the West Bank in protest against a
just-concluded visit to the Palestinian self-rule areas by French
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 Hebron University students set afire French national
flags and Jospin's photos, according to eyewitnesses. And the
protesters chanted anti-French slogans such as "Jospin, Take off
the Mask, Show Your Jewish Face."
</P>
<P>
The protests, which entered its second day on Sunday, were
triggered by Jospin's remarks during his visit to Israel on
Thursday that the Lebanese Hezbollah guerrilla group was "
terrorist."
</P>
<P>
The words aroused widespread criticism by Lebanon and the whole
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday morning students of the Birzeit University threw
stones at Jospin and his entourage during his visit to the
university. One of the journalists was slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat apologized to Jospin at a press
conference held at his presidential office here Saturday afternoon
on behalf of himself, the Palestinian people and the university.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told Jospin that the incident was totally "condemnable"
and that he had ordered the closure of the university for three
days pending investigation.
</P>
<P>
He described those who stoned Jospin as "force of darkness
rather than representatives of the Palestinian people and
students".
</P>
<P>
Palestinian police chief in the Gaza Strip Mohammed Dahlan said
that Arafat told the security agencies in the West Bank to
investigate into the incident in full within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jospin said he understood what had happened in
Birzeit, denying that the incident would affect the French-
Palestinian ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Slams U.S. Report on Human Rights Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Hamid-Reza Asefi on Sunday categorically dismissed the
allegations made by the U.S. State Department on human rights
situation in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Terming the allegations as unfounded and biased, Asefi described
the U.S. State Department's annual report as an attempt to mislead
the world public opinion, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. administration has failed to accurately
evaluate the human rights situation in the Islamic Republic of
Iran.
</P>
<P>
"The magnificent parliamentary elections (held on February 18)
with the massive turnout displayed an example of democracy and
reinforcing the law as well as respecting the nation's votes and
honoring their rights," Asefi said.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. State Department has released annual report on
human rights in the world while the U.S. community suffers from the
worst kind of human rights violation, racial discrimination,
violence, torture and mistreatment of prisoners.
</P>
<P>
He added that violation of human rights in the U.S. is the prime
concern of the human rights organizations and the other non-
governmental humanitarian agencies.
</P>
<P>
Human rights are always respected in the Islamic Republic of
Iran thanks to the Islamic teachings which require the Islamic
government to do so, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Republic of Iran respects the human rights on the
basis of its religious belief, the stipulations of the constitution
and regards it as the national and international commitment," he
said, noting that the government has put the issue of human rights
as the fundamental aspect of its platform.
</P>
<P>
The impartial international observers have admitted that the
Iranian government is committed to its obligations concerning human
rights.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman advised the U.S. statesmen to think about
improving the human rights record in their own country instead of
making biased report on human rights record in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French FM Defends Jospin's Statement on Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine Sunday defended the statement made by Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin on the Lebanese guerrilla group Hezbollah, saying
that Jospin's words were founded on his "heart and conviction."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Radio-Television Luxembourg and LCI
television channels, Vedrine said that "extremist forces" always
want to break up the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
But he refrained from defining the actions of Hezbollah
guerrillas against Israeli troops as "terrorism," as Jospin did
Thursday in Jerusalem during his visit in Israel.
</P>
<P>
"This is not the first time in the Middle East that each time
when people move forward (in the peace process), you have the
extremist forces who want to break up the movement," said the
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He said that the military operations in southern Lebanon
launched by Hezbollah have the clear objective of "thwarting this
perspective" of peace.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also said that the statement of Jospin does not mean
that France's position on the Middle East, which he described as
an engagement for peace, has changed.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that the Socialist government wants to "give
more body and substance to the relations with Israel."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that as Israel is preparing to pull
out its troops from southern Lebanon, all the sides involved in
the conflict should refrain from taking any military action.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that some leaders in the Middle East don't know
how to seize a chance of peace after Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak came to power last May.
</P>
<P>
"This hope (for peace) is in the process of turning into
impatience and worry," said Vedrine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
