<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Urged to Play Leading Role in ECOWAS Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A visiting senior official of
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) said Sunday
that Nigeria could play a leading role in accelerating the
organization's integration process.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate was speaking at the
Nigerian House of Representatives Committee on Cooperation and
Integration in Africa in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
He said Nigeria, with the restoration of democracy after long
military rule, could play a leading role in the realization of the
objectives of the 16-member organization, most of whose programs
had been stalled by lack of leadership.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate said ECOWAS, with a population of about 250 million,
must integrate its economy in order to survive in the
globalization.
</P>
<P>
"This is the only option for us if we are not to be
marginalized in the international economic arena," he said, adding
that this was the only way that Africa could overcome the legacies
of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate said that the sub-region had all the ingredients for
economic progress, including the size of its population as well as
its human and material resources, which should be used to generate
the momentum for economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged To Prepare WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 27 (Xinhua) -- African countries need to
consult extensively and involve all stakeholders in preparing
their positions for the World Trade Organization (WTO) talks, a
leading Zimbabwean development consultant said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Imani Development Consultant Executive Richard Hess was
speaking at a three-day workshop organized by the Southern African
Regional Institute for Policy Studies in Harare to deliberate on
emerging trade links on the back of rapid globalization.
</P>
<P>
"There needs to be a consultative mechanism in each country to
discuss and prepare positions for negotiators, this body should
have a strong private sector representation as well as
representation from all relevant government departments," he said.
</P>
<P>
A WTO Ministerial Conference held in Seattle, the United
States, late last year was aborted after developing countries
refused to be arm-twisted into accepting the principles governing
a free global economy that they felt would prejudice them.
</P>
<P>
The WTO general council is preparing another attempt to push
its proposals through and the break should give African countries
extra time to prepare their arguments, Hess said.
</P>
<P>
"Although the agenda has not been set for any new round, dates
have already been set for commencing the previously-mandated work
in services and agriculture," he said.
</P>
<P>
The first session on agriculture is scheduled for March 20 this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
