<HEADLINE> Nigeria Stresses Traditional Rulers' Role in Social Harmony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Vice President Atiku
Abubakar has called on the nation's traditional rulers to ensure
the peaceful co- existence among the diverse ethnic groups in
their domains, the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Calling them custodians of the country's unique culture, he
said in Lafia traditional ruler's domain in central Nigeria's
Nassarawa State that " what has happened in Kaduna State is
something to be condemned by all decent human beings".
</P>
<P>
About 300 people died in last week's clash between Christians
and Moslems in the country's northern city Kaduna.
</P>
<P>
The NAN quoted Abubakar as saying in a turbaning ceremony
performed by the Emir of Lafia, Assarawa State, at which the
Nassarawa State's Governor Alhaji Adamu presented the traditional
ruler with the staff of office.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that irrespective of their ethnic differences and
religious background, Nigerians should live with each other in
peace and harmony.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Senate President Chuba Okadigbo and Speaker of the
House of Representatives Alhaji Na'abba were among the guests to
attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000227.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods in Southern Mozambique Continue to Worsen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Flooding in the city of
Xai-Xai, capital of the southern Mozambican Province of Gaza, has
continued to worsen over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
By Sunday morning, according to Radio Mozambique, the flood
waters of the Limpopo river had split the city in two, cutting off
the main commercial part of Xai-Xai from the higher part of the
city.
</P>
<P>
The city is without electricity because the floods have swamped
the Xai- Xai power station. The lack of power makes it impossible
to work electric pumps, and so shortly the city will run out of
fresh water as well.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, those who had ignored earlier appeals from the
provincial authorities to leave the low-lying part of the city
were trying frantically to leave Xai-Xai on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A new flood peak is moving down the river. On Saturday night
this new wall of water hit the town of Chokwe on the middle
Limpopo.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that this new flood wave could bring the height of
the river at Chokwe to over 10 metres. This would be two metres
higher than the highest level the Limpopo reached during the
massive floods of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Much of the population of Chokwe had already left the town
during the flooding early this mouth. Some of those who declined
to leave then are now making their way to the town of Macia, some
50 kilometers south-west, and one of the parts of the province not
affected by floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
