<HEADLINE> British Officials Own Land In Zimbabwe: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
resisting Zimbabwe's efforts to compulsorily acquire land for
re-distribution because some of its top officials, including its
Minister of State in the Foreign Office Peter Hain, owns land in
Zimbabwe, the Sunday Mail newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Minister of Local Government and National Housing
John Nkomo, who is also the National Chairman of the ruling party
Zanu-pf, confirmed the reports, saying that he had personally
quizzed Hain over the issue.
</P>
<P>
There has been no comment from Hain yet. However, British
Deputy High Commissioner in Zimbabwe Ian Hay Campbell said he
needs enough time to verify whether there are any British top
officials who own land in the African country.
</P>
<P>
On whether the British constitution allows foreigners to own
land in Britain, the deputy high commissioner said, "In Britain
there is no existence of anything that you can genuinely call a
constitution as one can find in other countries."
</P>
<P>
According to Nkomo, after being quizzed, Hain responded by
urging the Zimbabwean government to be forward looking instead of
reverting back to history.
</P>
<P>
"I told him that the history he wanted us to forget had a
bearing on the present status quo and that we can only solve the
present problems by addressing the injustices of the past," Nkomo
said.
</P>
<P>
Without divulging any names, Nkomo said the British government
would be embarrassed if the top officials who own land in
Zimbabwe were to be exposed.
</P>
<P>
He said it was Hain who had written letters to the
International Monetary Fund instructing the institution not to
release any funds because of alleged "lack of democracy and human
rights abuses in Zimbabwe".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chairman of the Zimbabwe National Liberation War
Veterans Association Chenjerai Hunzvi Saturday said in Harare that
his association is aware that there are some British top officials
who have farms in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said the war veterans are going to grab all those farms
before the general elections in April because it is their
"birthright to own it".
</P>
<P>
"We are left with no option but to take all the farms whose
owners had gone to court to resist the acquisition," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
