<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's National Museum Damaged by Heavy Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains have destroyed
books and artifacts at the Livingstone Museum, Zambia's National
Museum, according to a report by the Sunday Times of Zambia
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the 50-year old two-storey building,
which has not had a major facelift since it was built, was last
week flooded with water leaking in through cracks on the roof and
walls after four days of continuous torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
The water, which also seeped into the main library on the first
floor, destroyed hundreds of rare books dating over a century ago
and which, according to director Vincent Katenekwa, are priceless
assets because they do not have back up copies.
</P>
<P>
Several artifacts were also soaked and arrangements were being
made to have them moved to a drier building, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The most affected part is the library, we have had to move the
whole library to a smaller drier room, most of the old books and
valuable photographs need attention," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the leaking was compounded by the fact that the
structure had a flat roof which retained water after heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
A rehabilitation project was planned in 1993 at a cost of
271,000 U.S. dollars but has since been gathering dust.
</P>
<P>
Located inside the Livingstone town, the Tourist capital of
Zambia in Southern Province, the national museum has exhibits that
record the complete history of human being in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is particularly well known for its collection relating to
the life and work of David Livingstone, including a notebook in
which the British explorer recorded the actual date on which he
first saw the Victoria Falls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
