<HEADLINE> Zambia to Fight Racism in Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government has called
for a meeting to review terms of reference of all lodge owners and
operators in Livingstone, a famous tourism city in the south of
the country, following persistent allegations of racism against
black tourists.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Times of Zambia quoted Acting Southern Province
Permanent Secretary Patrick Banda as saying that he will this week
hold a meeting with all the lodge and tour operators to resolve
the issue.
</P>
<P>
Some tour operators have been accused of blocking blacks from
staying at their lodges.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, I can confirm to you that we have been receiving numerous
 complaints about this segregation of who goes to this lodge and
who does not," said the official.
</P>
<P>
The accused tour operators are said to be advising would-be
black lodgers to make reservations through their overseas agents
when the lodges are not at full capacity, a move which has
frustrated the locals, according to the local newspaper. 
</P>
