<HEADLINE> Uganda Education Sets Staff Ceilings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
set staff establishment ceilings for all primary schools and
instructed districts to recruit teachers immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education and Sports has laid down a strict
timetable for the recruitment in order to enable the teachers to
get on to the payroll by May 10, the New Vision reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to ministry's timetable, all vacancies must be
advertised by the end of February and interviews are to be
conducted by the district service commissions beginning from
March 9 and letters of appointment issued before April 10.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it stipulated that all the necessary documentation
of the recruitment should reach the Ministry of Public Service
before April 26.
</P>
<P>
The report said that total primary teaching staff has been set
at 101, 601 teachers for the expected more than six million
pupils.
</P>
<P>
Since the country launched the Universal Primary Education
(UPE) program in January 1997, pupil enrolment in primary schools
has more than doubled. Now every district across the country is
lack of primary school teachers and classrooms. The UPE program,
which provides free primary school education for four children in
each family, is aimed to reduce illiteracy rate and widespread
poverty. At president, more than 40 percent of the population is
still illiterate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
