<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Urges Fewer Parties, Restoration of People's Faith </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Acting President
Vladimir Putin said Sunday that Russia should have fewer parties
and those parties should act as "a backbone for powerful national
spirit" to restore people's faith in the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Putin, addressing a conference of the Unity movement, said the
Russian people were tired of confrontational politics.
</P>
<P>
He said the presence of some 200 parties in Russia is not
beneficial for its political sphere. "A working system is a system
of two, three or four parties."
</P>
<P>
"Today it is clear to all that political confrontation has had
its day in Russia. The citizens of Russia are bored with
ideological battles," he said.
</P>
<P>
Putin, 47, became acting president after Boris Yeltsin's abrupt
resignation on December 31. He is the clear front-runner in the
presidential election on March 26.
</P>
<P>
Unity, set up last autumn to back Putin's presidential bid, is
the second biggest party in the new State Duma lower house of
parliament after the Communists. It gained a surprisingly strong
performance in December's Duma elections.
</P>
<P>
He said that Unity should become a strong, nationwide party to
rival the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that Unity too will become a truly representative,
strong and solid political force able to exert real influence on
the fate of the country and its regions," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Unity delegates elected Deputy Prime Minister Sergei Shoigu as
its formal party leader. Shoigu, who is also minister of emergency
situations, was a founding member of Unity.
</P>
<P>
Shoigu told the delegates that support for Putin in the
presidential race is the party's "first and main task." 
</P>
</TEXT>
